english:
  title: Night Musings in Response to Scholar Yongje's Verses on the First Day of Spring
  author: Park Eun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Lazy, I've ceased receiving visitors,
    Anxious, I toy with words to ease the pain.
    Though spring light delights the eye,
    The world shows me no mercy.

    I long to return to my humble farm,
    But sleeplessness stretches the spring night long.
    Yet I know that Master Lee understands—
    He alone can hear the music of solitude.

    What joy awaits tomorrow?
    The lamplight seems to mock me still.
    Spring sleep comes too sparse to bear,
    And a wanderer's sorrows multiply without end.
    How can I ever finish bearing this weight?
    Even those nearby now seem impossibly far.

    Before the wind, an old horse neighs,
    As if answering with a prolonged song.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The title indicates this is one of two poems responding to verses from Scholar Yongje (容齋學士) written for the First Day of Spring. The collection references the tradition of literary exchange during the spring festival.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Master Lee' (李夫子) likely refers to a respected scholar or friend whose philosophical understanding and empathy are contrasted with the speaker's isolation.
  - key: ''
    value: The final image of the old horse neighing before the wind carries both melancholy and a suggestion of perseverance—the horse, despite its age, still responds to the natural world.
